==Old English==
===Etymology===
Germanic ''*kuman-'', from Indo-European ''*gʷem-'' ‘come, go’.

''Germanic cognates:'' Old Frisian [[kuma]], Old Saxon [[cuman#Old Saxon|cuman]] (Dutch [[komen]]), Old High German [[queman]] (German [[kommen]]), Old Norse [[koma]] (Swedish [[komma]]), Gothic [[𐌵𐌹𐌼𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/kʊman/}}

===Verb===
'''cuman''' (class IV strong: ''3 singular present'' '''[[cymþ]]''', ''3 singular preterite'' {{Unicode|'''[[com#Old English|cōm]]'''}}, ''preterite plural'' {{Unicode|'''[[comon|cōmon]]'''}}, ''past participle'' (ġe)'''[[cumen]]''')
# to [[come]]
#:''Sceal se gast cuman'': the spirit shall come.

